                <p>*Departed at 10:00 a.m.</p>
                <p>**Not present for final item</p>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="italic">SUMMARY OF CONCLUSIONS</hi>
                </p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> reviewed a series of papers on proposals
                    for increasing economic and military assistance to Pakistan,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d402fn2">A January 3 memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_SHH_1"
                            >Saunders</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_NDD_1">Newsom</persName>,
                        entitled “<gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> Meeting January 4: Economic
                        Assistance for Pakistan,” recommended giving Pakistan $100 million in <gloss
                            target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> for <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss>
                        1980 and $100 million in <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1981. For both
                        years, the suggested programming of the funds was $60 million for fertilizer
                        imports, $25 million for rural electrification, and $15 million for rural
                        roads. (National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central
                        Foreign Policy File, P800028–0122) No paper on military assistance was
                        found, but see <ref target="#d405fn13">footnote 13, Document
                        405</ref>.</note> development of an emergency fund to cover unanticipated
                    expenses related to the Southwest Asia crisis, and the possibility of seeking
                    legislative relief from certain restrictions on Presidential action.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d402fn3">Neither of these papers was found.</note> It was decided to
                    proceed as follows:</p>
                <p>1. <hi rend="italic">Symington Amendment</hi>. All agreed that our first priority
                    must be to lift the legislative restrictions which currently prevent U.S.
                    assistance to Pakistan. The <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> staff will work
                    with State in refining the draft bill which State had prepared for the meeting.
                    (C)</p>
                <pb facs="0942" n="897" xml:id="pg_897"/>
                <p>2. <hi rend="italic">Supplemental Funding for Pakistan</hi>. <gloss
                        target="#t_OMB_1">OMB</gloss> will work with State on a recommended funding
                    level for a supplemental. This subject will be reviewed at the meeting on
                        Monday.<note n="4" xml:id="d402fn4">January 7.</note> The <gloss
                        target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> noted the discussion at the President’s
                    Foreign Policy Breakfast earlier in the morning where a funding level of $100
                    million in <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">FMS</gloss> credits and $100 million in
                        <gloss target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> was considered.<note n="5"
                        xml:id="d402fn5">According to the President’s Daily Diary, from 7:30 to 9:15
                        a.m., January 4, <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> met with
                            <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1">Vance</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BHS_1">Brown</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_DHW_1"
                            >Donovan</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_JH_1">Jordan</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_CL_2">Cutler</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName> in the Cabinet Room. (Carter
                        Library, Presidential Materials) No record of the meeting was found.</note>
                    It was agreed that we should inform both Pakistan and India in advance of any
                    decisions. (S)</p>
                <p>3. <hi rend="italic">Increasing the Discretionary Authority of the
                    President</hi>. The <gloss target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> agreed that we should
                    use this opportunity to seek relief from certain legislative restrictions beyond
                    the Symington Amendment as feasible. The test would be feasibility. We want to
                    avoid a Legislative-Executive battle over prerogatives which could distract from
                    or derail the Pakistan effort. State and the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                        >NSC</gloss> will work together to identify restrictions which are
                    troublesome and which might feasibly be waived in the context of the crisis.
                    (S)</p>
                <p>4. <hi rend="italic">Pakistan Debt Relief</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_OHD_1"
                        >Henry Owen</persName> noted that debt relief might be an even more
                    effective means of assisting Pakistan than <gloss target="#t_FMS_1"
                        >FMS</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss>. He will work with
                    Treasury and State to develop a paper on this option for consideration next
                    Monday. (C)</p>
                <p>5. <hi rend="italic">Security Consortium</hi>. All agreed that it might be useful
                    to develop a consortium of nations to assist Pakistani security. A consortium
                    already exists on the economic side. However, it would be desirable for another
                    nation—perhaps Pakistan itself—to take the lead in forming such a group, and we
                    would wish to insure that it did not slow down our ability to act quickly. State
                    will prepare a paper on a strategy of how we could best pursue the consortium
                    option. (C)</p>
                <p>6. <hi rend="italic">Arms for Pakistan</hi>. A Defense paper was reviewed, which
                    provided a series of options on the type of military equipment (and costs) which
                    we might be willing to provide. The key question will be whether or not we are
                    willing to provide advanced aircraft, including the possibility of the FX, which
                    has now been approved for development. An alternative approach would be to focus
                    on defensive equipment which Pakistan could use for self-defense in the event
                    the conflict in Afghanistan spills across the border. The latter would include
                    anti-tank weapons, howitzers, and tanks. Defense noted that many of the
                    items—including M48 tanks—would have to be drawn from current inventories and
                    would have a significant impact on U.S. force readiness. The <gloss
                        target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> agreed that the possible packages needed to be
                    better defined in terms of alternatives. State and Defense will prepare a paper
                    defining <pb facs="0943" n="898" xml:id="pg_898"/> the options and examining the
                    guidance which we could provide to a military survey team, assuming Pakistan
                    accepts our offer. (S)</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Intelligence Issues</p>
                <p>[<hi rend="italic">3 paragraphs (18 lines) not declassified</hi>]<note n="6"
                        xml:id="d402fn6">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> checked the Approve option,
                        below which he initialed “J.” To the right of the options, <persName
                            corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote: “Give me a breakdown,
                        J.”.</note>
                </p>
